# Add New Service Class

Create a service following SOLID principles with proper dependency injection.

## Service Requirements
1. Define interface `I<ServiceName>` with clear contract
2. Implement in `<ServiceName>` class
3. Inject dependencies via constructor (ILogger, IConfiguration, other services)
4. Add XML documentation for public methods
5. Handle errors appropriately (exceptions or error tuples)
6. Register in `Program.cs` with appropriate lifetime
7. Keep methods focused and small (Single Responsibility)

## Service Template
```csharp
namespace CV_extractor;

/// <summary>
/// Interface for <ServiceName> defining the contract.
/// </summary>
public interface I<ServiceName>
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Brief description of method.
    /// </summary>
    /// <param name="parameter">Parameter description</param>
    /// <returns>Return value description</returns>
    ReturnType MethodName(ParameterType parameter);
}

/// <summary>
/// Implementation of I<ServiceName>.
/// </summary>
public class <ServiceName> : I<ServiceName>
{
    private readonly ILogger<<ServiceName>> _logger;
    
    public <ServiceName>(ILogger<<ServiceName>> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }
    
    public ReturnType MethodName(ParameterType parameter)
    {
        // Implementation
        _logger.LogInformation("Action performed");
        return result;
    }
}
```

## Service with Error Tuple Pattern (like SkillExtractorService)
```csharp
namespace CV_extractor;

public interface IDataProcessorService
{
    (ProcessedData? data, string? error, int statusCode) ProcessData(InputData input);
}

public class DataProcessorService : IDataProcessorService
{
    public (ProcessedData? data, string? error, int statusCode) ProcessData(InputData input)
    {
        // Validate input
        if (!IsValidInput(input))
            return (null, "Invalid input message", StatusCodes.Status400BadRequest);
        
        // Process with error handling
        try
        {
            var data = PerformProcessing(input);
            return (data, null, StatusCodes.Status200OK);
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            return (null, $"Processing failed: {ex.Message}", StatusCodes.Status500InternalServerError);
        }
    }
    
    private static bool IsValidInput(InputData input)
    {
        // Validation logic
        return input != null;
    }
    
    private static ProcessedData PerformProcessing(InputData input)
    {
        // Processing logic
        return new ProcessedData();
    }
}
```

## Registration in Program.cs
```csharp
// Choose appropriate lifetime:

// Scoped: Created once per request (default for most services)
builder.Services.AddScoped<I<ServiceName>, <ServiceName>>();

// Singleton: Created once for app lifetime (stateless, shared state)
builder.Services.AddSingleton<I<ServiceName>, <ServiceName>>();

// Transient: Created every time it's requested (lightweight, stateless)
builder.Services.AddTransient<I<ServiceName>, <ServiceName>>();
```

## Service Lifetime Guidelines
- **Scoped**: Use for services that need request-specific state or work with database contexts
- **Singleton**: Use for stateless services, configuration readers, caching services
- **Transient**: Use for lightweight services with no state, utility services

## Method Organization
```csharp
public class WellOrganizedService : IWellOrganizedService
{
    // 1. Private fields
    private readonly IDependency _dependency;
    private const string SomeConstant = "value";
    
    // 2. Constructor
    public WellOrganizedService(IDependency dependency)
    {
        _dependency = dependency;
    }
    
    // 3. Public interface methods
    public ReturnType PublicMethod(Parameters params)
    {
        return PrivateHelperMethod(params);
    }
    
    // 4. Private instance methods
    private ReturnType PrivateHelperMethod(Parameters params)
    {
        return StaticUtilityMethod(params);
    }
    
    // 5. Private static methods (pure functions)
    private static ReturnType StaticUtilityMethod(Parameters params)
    {
        // Pure logic with no dependencies
        return result;
    }
}
```

## Error Handling Patterns

### Pattern 1: Exception Throwing (for exceptional cases)
```csharp
public void ValidateAndProcess(Data data)
{
    if (data == null)
        throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(data));
    
    if (!IsValid(data))
        throw new InvalidOperationException("Data validation failed");
    
    // Process
}
```

### Pattern 2: Tuple Returns (for expected error cases)
```csharp
public (Result? result, string? error) TryProcess(Data data)
{
    if (!IsValid(data))
        return (null, "Validation failed");
    
    try
    {
        var result = Process(data);
        return (result, null);
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        return (null, $"Processing error: {ex.Message}");
    }
}
```

### Pattern 3: Result Object (for complex scenarios)
```csharp
public class OperationResult<T>
{
    public bool Success { get; init; }
    public T? Data { get; init; }
    public string? Error { get; init; }
    public int StatusCode { get; init; }
}

public OperationResult<ProcessedData> Process(InputData input)
{
    // Implementation
}
```

## Checklist
- [ ] Interface defined with XML comments
- [ ] Implementation class created
- [ ] Dependencies injected via constructor
- [ ] XML documentation on public methods
- [ ] Error handling implemented
- [ ] Private helper methods extracted
- [ ] Service registered in Program.cs with correct lifetime
- [ ] Unit tests created for service
